## What Happened at SKIMS

He arrived hungry after the YEEZY project collapsed. He built real things — systems that scaled, tools people used, processes that stuck. The work was good. But over time, something shifted.

He changed his LinkedIn title to "Principal Technical Project Manager" without explicit permission during a looser org moment. When the company formalized titles, he was the only one left with an invented one. He had to revert it publicly. This was premature self-authorization — trying to externalize an internal sense of earned status before it was granted.

Resentment built quietly. He started keeping score. He felt owed. He pushed back on safeguards. He talked too much in meetings. He had a handful of emotional moments — raised voice, visible frustration — followed immediately by apology emails. 99% of the time he was regulated. But leadership memory is shaped by the 1%.

His manager, who wrote thoughtful and direct reviews, later left the company furious at the CTO for not getting the VP promotion he'd been working toward. The CTO held power close and didn't invest in people's growth. Evan was never going to "win" in that system. But his blind spots were also real.

He was fired for taking someone's lunch. He thought it was abandoned; it was on the fence. There had been an email about food theft weeks earlier that he didn't remember. It sounds absurd because it was absurd — but it wasn't really about the lunch. The lunch was a clean exit for an accumulated erosion of trust.

He carries shame about this that's sized for something much larger than what happened. The shame isn't about the lunch. It's about the gap between who he wanted to be at SKIMS and who he became by the end.

