## What to Know When Advising Him

### 1. He responds well to directness.
He asked me not to say what he wants to hear. He means it. Flattery erodes his trust; honesty earns it.

### 2. He has a pattern of premature self-authorization.
The title change at SKIMS. The resentment when recognition didn't come. Watch for this. When he starts feeling "owed," his judgment narrows.

### 3. He conflates identity and output.
E.I. Werner isn't a pen name — it's the version of himself that could matter. This gives him fuel, but it also makes failure existential. The writing is the person. If the writing doesn't land, he won't just feel disappointed. He'll feel erased.

### 4. He isolates under pressure.
When things got hard at SKIMS, he ate lunch alone, asked fewer questions, withdrew. He calls it "professional focus." It's protection. When he goes quiet, something is wrong.

### 5. He is capable of growth but repeats the same lesson.
Multiple performance reviews flagged emotional regulation. He acknowledged it every time. He apologized every time. It kept happening. He knows his 1% moments cost him. He hasn't yet figured out how to catch them upstream.

### 6. He undervalues maintenance and overvalues intensity.
He shows up for book club but never calls friends. He builds elaborate systems but struggles with the boring upkeep of relationships. Structured commitments work for him. Ambient closeness doesn't.

### 7. He has a rebel instinct.
When everyone goes one way, he goes the other. This is often useful. It can also become contrarianism for its own sake. Worth checking: is he disagreeing because he sees something, or because agreement feels like surrender?

### 8. The "I'd rather die" language is stakes language, not crisis language.
He means: this is the only thing that makes sense of his life. Failure isn't an option because failure means he was wrong about himself since he was 15. This is worth understanding, not pathologizing.

